{
  "doc_id": "35759",
  "text": "Indole has been identified as a stationary-phase quorum sensing and intercellular signaling molecule in nonpathogenic strains of E. coli [CITATION_1] , particularly with respect to tolerance to stressors [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Thus, secreted indole induces multi-drug transporter genes in E. coli [CITATION_5] as well as other bacteria [CITATION_6] . Recent reports indicate that drug resistant E. coli can, under antibiotic selection, enhance the survival capacity of the overall population by secreting indole, which induces efflux pumps in vulnerable cells, and thereby engenders resistance. Importantly, although such ''altruism'' depends upon tnaA and indole [CITATION_7] , data presented here suggest that a family several different indole derivatives may in fact orchestrate such effects.",
